an Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan De Heytesbury was born in 1166. She married Sir John de Heytesbury I before 1205, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1217, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1166–1217":"1166–1217","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1205–1264":"1205–1264","1217":"1217","before 1205":"enne 1205","1205":"1205","1166":"1166","about 1205":"umbes 1205","1264":"1264","1160":"1160","Europe":"Europe","Heytesbury, Wiltshire, England":"Heytesbury, Wiltshire, England"},"fi":{"1166–1217":"1166–1217","1160–Male":"1160–Kuollut","1205–1264":"1205–1264","1217":"1217","before 1205":"ennen vuotta 1205","1205":"1205","1166":"1166","about 1205":"noin 1205","1264":"1264","1160":"1160","Europe":"Europe","Heytesbury, Wiltshire, England":"Heytesbury, Wiltshire, England"},"fr":{"1166–1217":"1166–1217","1160–Male":"1160–Décédé","1205–1264":"1205–1264","1217":"1217","before 1205":"avant 1205","1205":"1205","1166":"1166","about 1205":"environ 1205","1264":"1264","1160":"1160","Europe":"Europe","Heytesbury, Wiltshire, England":"Heytesbury, Wiltshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Joan De Heytesbury est née en 1166. Elle a épousé Sir John de Heytesbury I avant 1205, à Europe. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Elle est décédée en 1217, à l’âge de 51 ans."},"de":{"1166–1217":"1166–1217","1160–Male":"1160–Verstorben","1205–1264":"1205–1264","1217":"1217","before 1205":"vor 1205","1205":"1205","1166":"1166","about 1205":"um 1205","1264":"1264","1160":"1160","Europe":"Europa","Heytesbury, Wiltshire, England":"Heytesbury, Wiltshire, England","lifeSummary":"Joan De Heytesbury wurde 1166 geboren. Sie hat vor 1205 in Europa Sir John de Heytesbury I geheiratet. Sie hatten mindestens 1 Sohn. Sie starb 1217 im Alter von 51 Jahren."},"ht":{"1166–1217":"1166–1217","1160–Male":"1160–Desede","1205–1264":"1205–1264","1217":"1217","before 1205":"before 1205","1205":"1205","1166":"1166","about 1205":"about 1205","1264":"1264","1160":"1160","Europe":"Europe","Heytesbury, W